# Issue Title

Debugger exited with COR_E_EXECUTIONENGINE on netcoreapp2.0 with special code

# General

Provide details on the problem you are experiencing including the .NET Core version, operating system version and anything else that is relevant.
Test on 
1. Win10x64(17046/16299), debug with VS2017 15.6p1 or VSCode_x64 1.18.1/1.20.0-insider(with `C#` plugin 1.13.1).

Crash with `System.ExecutionEngineException` on `net471`.
Crash with `COR_E_EXECUTIONENGINE` on `netcoreapp2.0` and `2.1(preview)`.
Works well with `netcoreapp1.1`.

Please provide a code sample for your issue if it is relevant, either inline, link to a gist (or similar) or add it as a zipped attachment.
```cs
using System;
class Program
{
    public abstract class T1
    {
        public byte data = 1;
        public virtual byte Data => data;
        public virtual void Test()
        {
            Console.WriteLine("T1");
            //Not happen after uncomment this
            //Console.WriteLine(Environment.StackTrace);
        }
    }
    public class T2 : T1
    {
        public override void Test()
        {
            //new csproj format, and TargetFramework: net461 or netcoreapp2.0
            //1. Set an breakpoint here, disable `Just My Code`, and debug with Release build(Debug works well)
            //2.1 Expand `this` or wath `this.Data`, `this.ToString()` or some others
            //2.2 Or type `this.Data`/`this.GetType().Name` in immediately window(System.ExecutionEngineException, exit after continue, but if you don't contine and type again, you can get the result).
            base.Test();
            //Not happen after uncomment this
            //Console.WriteLine("T2");
        }
    }
    private static T1 t1 = new T2();
    private static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        try {
            t1.Test();
        }catch(Exception e){
            Console.Error.WriteLine(e);
        }
        Console.ReadLine();
    }
}
```
1. Change `configuration` from `Debug` to `Release`
2. Disable `JustMyCode`
3. Set an breakpoint at `base.Test()`
4. Start Debug
5. Add watch to `this.Data` or `this.ToString()` or just expand `this`
6.1 See debuger exit with `COR_E_EXECUTIONENGINE`(`0x80131506`) on `netcoreapp2.0`
6.2 On net471, an `System.ExecutionEngineException` is get instead.
6.3 On VS2017's immediately window and net471, if not click continue after expection, and watch again, it can get the result.
6.4 When set another breakpoint at `t1.Test()`, and watch `t1.Data` first and continue to next breakpoint, it works well.

